(1) Washington Street, east side, between Johnson Street and Myrtle Ave. A view of the "Commonwealth Hall" at No. 323-327 Washington Street. The segment of a building No. 319, visible at left, housed the (Central Post Office) of the City of Brooklyn until 1892, when it was removed to the Federal Building, white structure, shadowing the view at the extreme left. 1909.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2) The same, "16" years later, showing the center building occupied by the post office of the City of Brooklyn until 1892, which is partially seen in view No. 1. The building to the left, No. 315 Washington Street, was occupied at one time (1880-?) by the police department of the City of Brooklyn. The 4-story building at right, remodeled was the "Commonwealth House" in view No. 1.

March 1925.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

185-191 Washington Street, east side, between Nassau and Concord Streets, showing 189 (next to the 1-story building), the A.A. Low home, birthplace of Seth Low. The building following it (187) was the Howard residence; in which Henry Ward Beecher stayed when he first began preaching in Brooklyn. It was demolished in 1928.

1923.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

268 to 258 Washington Street, west side, at Tillary Street, looking north toward the B. M. T. elevated car yards. These buildings, among others, were later demolished and the area incorporated into the new approach to the Brooklyn Bridge. View 2 shows the area after the buildings were razed and the construction, by the W. P. A., of the bridge approach, the view being north; view 3 is west on Tillary Street, toward Fulton Street.

View 1: November, 1935
Views 2, 3: August 20, 1936

149 Washington Street, east side, between High (foreground) and Sands Streets, showing the Washington Hotel for men. This view also shows the High and Sands Streets stations of the Lexington and Myrtle Ave. Lines (B.M.T.).

May 24, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

155-157 Washington Street, at the N.E. corner of High Street, showing the High Street station of the Myrtle (B.M.T.) Ave. Elevated Line. The Heights moving picture theatre stood on the site of the drug store (no. 155) in 1929.

May 24, 1937.
